# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: poisson-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] In statistics, **count data** is a statistical data type describing *countable quantities*, data which can take only the *counting numbers*, non-negative integer values {0, 1, 2, 3, ...}, and where these integers arise from *counting* rather than ranking.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] An individual piece of count data is often termed a **count variable**.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] When such a variable is treated as a random variable, the Poisson, binomial and negative binomial distributions are commonly used to represent its distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] Graphical examination of count data may be aided by the use of data transformations chosen to have the property of stabilising the sample variance.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] In particular, the square root transformation might be used when data can be approximated by a Poisson distribution (although other transformation have modestly improved properties), while an inverse sine transformation is available when a binomial distribution is preferred.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] Here the count variable would be treated as a dependent variable.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] Statistical methods such as least squares and analysis of variance are designed to deal with continuous dependent variables.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] These can be adapted to deal with count data by using data transformations such as the square root transformation, but such methods have several drawbacks; they are approximate at best and estimate parameters that are often hard to interpret.
[src:poisson-regression/count-data] The Poisson distribution can form the basis for some analyses of count data and in this case Poisson regression may be used.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] (Sometimes the roles are swapped: the number of failures is fixed and the number of successes is modeled.) For example, we can define rolling a 6 on some dice as a success, and rolling any other number as a failure, and ask how many failure rolls will occur before we see the third success ( $r=3$ ).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In such a case, the probability distribution of the number of failures that appear will be a negative binomial distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] An alternative formulation is to model the number of total trials (instead of the number of failures).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In fact, for a specified (non-random) number of successes (*r*), the number of failures (*n* − *r*) is random because the number of total trials (*n*) is random.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] For example, we could use the negative binomial distribution to model the number of days n (random) a certain machine works (specified by r) before it breaks down.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution has a variance $\mu /p$ , with the distribution becoming identical to Poisson in the limit $p\to 1$ for a given mean $\mu$ (i.e. when the failures are increasingly rare).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Here $p\in [0,1]$ is the success probability of each Bernoulli trial.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This can make the distribution a useful overdispersed alternative to the Poisson distribution, for example for a robust modification of Poisson regression.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In epidemiology, it has been used to model disease transmission for infectious diseases where the likely number of onward infections may vary considerably from individual to individual and from setting to setting.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] More generally, it may be appropriate where events have positively correlated occurrences causing a larger variance than if the occurrences were independent, due to a positive covariance term.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The term "negative binomial" is likely due to the fact that a certain binomial coefficient that appears in the formula for the probability mass function of the distribution can be written more simply with negative numbers.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Imagine a sequence of independent Bernoulli trials: each trial has two potential outcomes called "success" and "failure." In each trial the probability of success is p and of failure is $1-p$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] We observe this sequence until a predefined number r of successes occurs.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The probability mass function of the negative binomial distribution is $f(k;r,p)\equiv \Pr(X=k)={\binom {k+r-1}{k}}(1-p)^{k}p^{r}$ where r is the number of successes, *X* = *k* is the number of failures before the r-th success, and p is the probability of success on each trial.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] There are k failures chosen from *k* + *r* − 1 trials rather than *k* + *r* because the last of the *k* + *r* trials is by definition a success.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] To understand the above definition of the probability mass function, note that the probability for every specific sequence of r successes and k failures is *p**r*(1 − *p*)*k*, because the outcomes of the *k* + *r* trials are supposed to happen independently.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Since the r-th success always comes last, it remains to choose the k trials with failures out of the remaining *k* + *r* − 1 trials.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The above binomial coefficient, due to its combinatorial interpretation, gives precisely the number of all these sequences of length *k* + *r* − 1.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] An alternate interpretation of the probability mass function's binomial coefficient arises when considering the equivalent multiset coefficient $\textstyle \left(\!\!{r \choose k}\!\!\right)$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] A sequence of trials ending in r successes can be represented by a tuple of r non-negative integers, where each integer represents the number of failures seen before the next success.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Then by applying stars and bars, it can be seen that the number of such tuples that sum to k (and hence represent k total failures and r total successes) is given by $\textstyle \left(\!\!{r \choose k}\!\!\right)$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Some sources may define the negative binomial distribution slightly differently from the primary one here.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The most common variations are where the random variable X is counting different things.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Each of the four definitions of the negative binomial distribution can be expressed in slightly different but equivalent ways.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The first alternative formulation is simply an equivalent form of the binomial coefficient, that is: ${\textstyle {\binom {a}{b}}={\binom {a}{a-b}}\quad {\text{for }}\ 0\leq b\leq a}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The second alternate formulation somewhat simplifies the expression by recognizing that the total number of trials is simply the number of successes and failures, that is: ${\textstyle n=r+k}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] These second formulations may be more intuitive to understand, however they are perhaps less practical as they have more terms.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In negative binomial regression, the distribution is specified in terms of its mean, ${\textstyle m={\frac {r(1-p)}{p}}}$ , which is then related to explanatory variables as in linear regression or other generalized linear models.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] From the expression for the mean m, one can derive ${\textstyle p={\frac {r}{m+r}}}$ and ${\textstyle 1-p={\frac {m}{m+r}}}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Some authors prefer to set ${\textstyle \alpha ={\frac {1}{r}}}$ , and express the variance as ${\textstyle m+\alpha m^{2}}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In this context, and depending on the author, either the parameter r or its reciprocal α is referred to as the "dispersion parameter", "shape parameter" or "clustering coefficient", or the "heterogeneity" or "aggregation" parameter.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The term "aggregation" is particularly used in ecology when describing counts of individual organisms.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Decrease of the aggregation parameter r towards zero corresponds to increasing aggregation of the organisms; increase of r towards infinity corresponds to absence of aggregation, as can be described by Poisson regression.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Hospital length of stay is an example of real-world data that can be modelled well with a negative binomial distribution via negative binomial regression.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Pat Collis is required to sell candy bars to raise money for the 6th grade field trip.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Pat is (somewhat harshly) not supposed to return home until five candy bars have been sold.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] So the child goes door to door, selling candy bars.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] At each house, there is a 0.6 probability of selling one candy bar and a 0.4 probability of selling nothing.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Successfully selling candy enough times is what defines our stopping criterion (as opposed to failing to sell it), so k in this case represents the number of failures and r represents the number of successes.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Recall that the NB(*r*, *p*) distribution describes the probability of k failures and r successes in *k* + *r* Bernoulli(*p*) trials with success on the last trial.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Selling five candy bars means getting five successes.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The number of trials (i.e. houses) this takes is therefore *k* + 5 = *n*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] To finish on or before the eighth house, Pat must finish at the fifth, sixth, seventh, or eighth house.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Because of the rather high probability that Pat will sell to each house (60 percent), the probability of her *not* fulfilling her quest is vanishingly slim.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The expected total number of trials needed to see r successes is ${\frac {r}{p}}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The expected total number of failures in a negative binomial distribution with parameters (*r*, *p*) is *r*(1 − *p*)/*p*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] To see this, imagine an experiment simulating the negative binomial is performed many times.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] That is, a set of trials is performed until r successes are obtained, then another set of trials, and then another etc.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Write down the number of trials performed in each experiment: *a*, *b*, *c*, ... and set *a* + *b* + *c* + ... = *N*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Now we would expect about *Np* successes in total.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Say the experiment was performed n times.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] See that *N*/*n* is just the average number of trials per experiment.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This agrees with the mean given in the box on the right-hand side of this page.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] A rigorous derivation can be done by representing the negative binomial distribution as the sum of waiting times.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Let $X_{r}\sim \operatorname {NB} (r,p)$ with the convention X represents the number of failures observed before r successes with the probability of success being p .
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] And let $Y_{i}\sim \mathrm {Geom} (p)$ where $Y_{i}$ represents the number of failures before seeing a success.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] We can think of $Y_{i}$ as the waiting time (number of failures) between the i th and $(i-1)$ th success.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] When counting the number of failures before the r-th success, the variance is *r*(1 − *p*)/*p*2.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] When counting the number of successes before the r-th failure, as in alternative formulation (3) above, the variance is *rp*/(1 − *p*)2.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Suppose Y is a random variable with a binomial distribution with parameters n and p.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] in which the upper bound of summation is infinite.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] is defined when n is a real number, instead of just a positive integer.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] But in our case of the binomial distribution it is zero when *k* > *n*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] is just the probability that the number of failures before the r-th success is equal to k, provided r is an integer.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Now we also allow non-integer values of r.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This property persists when the definition is thus generalized, and affords a quick way to see that the negative binomial distribution is infinitely divisible.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Consider a sequence of negative binomial random variables where the stopping parameter r goes to infinity, while the probability p of success in each trial goes to one, in such a way as to keep the mean of the distribution (i.e. the expected number of failures) constant.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In other words, the alternatively parameterized negative binomial distribution converges to the Poisson distribution and r controls the deviation from the Poisson.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution also arises as a continuous mixture of Poisson distributions (i.e. a compound probability distribution) where the mixing distribution of the Poisson rate is a gamma distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] That is, we can view the negative binomial as a Poisson(*λ*) distribution, where λ is itself a random variable, distributed as a gamma distribution with shape r and scale *θ* = (1 − *p*)/*p* or correspondingly rate *β* = *p*/(1 − *p*).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] To display the intuition behind this statement, consider two independent Poisson processes, "Success" and "Failure", with intensities p and 1 − *p*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Together, the Success and Failure processes are equivalent to a single Poisson process of intensity 1, where an occurrence of the process is a success if a corresponding independent coin toss comes up heads with probability p; otherwise, it is a failure.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] If r is a counting number, the coin tosses show that the count of successes before the r-th failure follows a negative binomial distribution with parameters r and 1 − *p*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The count is also, however, the count of the Success Poisson process at the random time T of the r-th occurrence in the Failure Poisson process.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The Success count follows a Poisson distribution with mean *pT*, where T is the waiting time for r occurrences in a Poisson process of intensity 1 − *p*, i.e., T is gamma-distributed with shape parameter r and intensity 1 − *p*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Thus, the negative binomial distribution is equivalent to a Poisson distribution with mean *pT*, where the random variate T is gamma-distributed with shape parameter r and intensity (1 − *p*).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The preceding paragraph follows, because *λ* = *pT* is gamma-distributed with shape parameter r and intensity (1 − *p*)/*p*.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The following formal derivation (which does not depend on r being a counting number) confirms the intuition.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Because of this, the negative binomial distribution is also known as the **gamma–Poisson (mixture) distribution**.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution was originally derived as a limiting case of the gamma-Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] If *Y**r* is a random variable following the negative binomial distribution with parameters r and p, and support {0, 1, 2, ...}, then *Y**r* is a sum of r independent variables following the geometric distribution (on {0, 1, 2, ...}) with parameter p.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] As a result of the central limit theorem, *Y**r* (properly scaled and shifted) is therefore approximately normal for sufficiently large r.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In this sense, the negative binomial distribution is the "inverse" of the binomial distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The sum of independent negative-binomially distributed random variables *r*1 and *r*2 with the same value for parameter p is negative-binomially distributed with the same p but with r-value *r*1 + *r*2.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution is infinitely divisible, i.e., if Y has a negative binomial distribution, then for any positive integer n, there exist independent identically distributed random variables *Y*1, ..., *Y**n* whose sum has the same distribution that Y has.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Let N be a random variable, independent of the sequence, and suppose that N has a Poisson distribution with mean λ = −*r* ln(1 − *p*).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] To prove this, we calculate the probability generating function *G**X* of X, which is the composition of the probability generating functions *G**N* and *G**Y*1.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] which is the probability generating function of the NB(*r*, *p*) distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This last expression can be written as ⁠ $C(1-pz)^{-r}$ ⁠ for a constant C.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The name "negative binomial distribution" is reflected in this binomial ⁠ $(1-pz)$ ⁠ with a negative term being raised to a negative power ⁠ $-r$ ⁠.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial, along with the Poisson and binomial distributions, is a member of the (*a*, *b*, 0) class of distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] All three of these distributions are special cases of the Panjer distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] They are also members of a natural exponential family.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Suppose p is unknown and an experiment is conducted where it is decided ahead of time that sampling will continue until r successes are found.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] A sufficient statistic for the experiment is k, the number of failures.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Its inverse (*r* + *k*)/*r*, is an unbiased estimate of 1/*p*, however.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] When r is unknown, the maximum likelihood estimator for p and r together only exists for samples for which the sample variance is larger than the sample mean.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This equation cannot be solved for r in closed form.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] If a numerical solution is desired, an iterative technique such as Newton's method can be used.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Alternatively, the expectation–maximization algorithm can be used.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Let k and r be integers with k non-negative and r positive.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In a sequence of independent Bernoulli trials with success probability p, the negative binomial gives the probability of k successes and r failures, with a failure on the last trial.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Therefore, the negative binomial distribution represents the probability distribution of the number of successes before the r-th failure in a Bernoulli process, with probability p of successes on each trial.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Suppose we repeatedly throw a die, and consider a 1 to be a failure.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The probability of success on each trial is 5/6.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The number of successes before the third failure belongs to the infinite set { 0, 1, 2, 3, ... }.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] That number of successes is a negative-binomially distributed random variable.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution, especially in its alternative parameterization described above, can be used as an alternative to the Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] It is especially useful for discrete data over an unbounded positive range whose sample variance exceeds the sample mean.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In such cases, the observations are overdispersed with respect to a Poisson distribution, for which the mean is equal to the variance.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Hence a Poisson distribution is not an appropriate model.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Since the negative binomial distribution has one more parameter than the Poisson, the second parameter can be used to adjust the variance independently of the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] See Cumulants of some discrete probability distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] An application of this is to annual counts of tropical cyclones in the North Atlantic or to monthly to 6-monthly counts of wintertime extratropical cyclones over Europe, for which the variance is greater than the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In the case of modest overdispersion, this may produce substantially similar results to an overdispersed Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Negative binomial modeling is widely employed in ecology and biodiversity research for analyzing count data where overdispersion is very common.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This is because overdispersion is indicative of biological aggregation, such as species or communities forming clusters.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Ignoring overdispersion can lead to significantly inflated model parameters, resulting in misleading statistical inferences.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The negative binomial distribution effectively addresses overdispersed counts by permitting the variance to vary quadratically with the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] An additional dispersion parameter governs the slope of the quadratic term, determining the severity of overdispersion.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The model's quadratic mean-variance relationship proves to be a realistic approach for handling overdispersion, as supported by empirical evidence from many studies.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Overall, the NB model offers two attractive features: (1) the convenient interpretation of the dispersion parameter as an index of clustering or aggregation, and (2) its tractable form, featuring a closed expression for the probability mass function.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In genetics, the negative binomial distribution is commonly used to model data in the form of discrete sequence read counts from high-throughput RNA and DNA sequencing experiments.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In epidemiology of infectious diseases, the negative binomial has been used as a better option than the Poisson distribution to model overdispersed counts of secondary infections from one infected case (super-spreading events).
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] The phenomenological justification for the effectiveness of the negative binomial distribution in these contexts remained unknown for fifty years, since their first observation in 1973.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] In 2023, a proof from first principles was eventually demonstrated by Scott V.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] Tezlaf, where it was shown that the negative binomial distribution emerges from symmetries in the dynamical equations of a canonical ensemble of particles in Minkowski space.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] A rigorous alternative proof of the above correspondence has also been demonstrated through quantum mechanics via the Feynman path integral.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] This distribution was first studied in 1713 by Pierre Remond de Montmort in his *Essay d'analyse sur les jeux de hazard*, as the distribution of the number of trials required in an experiment to obtain a given number of successes.
[src:poisson-regression/negative-binomial-distribution] It had previously been mentioned by Pascal.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] In statistics, **overdispersion** is the presence of greater variability (statistical dispersion) in a data set than would be expected based on a given statistical model.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] A common task in applied statistics is choosing a parametric model to fit a given set of empirical observations.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] This necessitates an assessment of the fit of the chosen model.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] It is usually possible to choose the model parameters in such a way that the theoretical population mean of the model is approximately equal to the sample mean.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] However, especially for simple models with few parameters, theoretical predictions may not match empirical observations for higher moments.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] When the observed variance is higher than the variance of a theoretical model, **overdispersion** has occurred.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Conversely, **underdispersion** means that there was less variation in the data than predicted.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Overdispersion is a very common feature in applied data analysis because in practice, populations are frequently heterogeneous (non-uniform) contrary to the assumptions implicit within widely used simple parametric models.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Overdispersion is often encountered when fitting very simple parametric models, such as those based on the Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] The Poisson distribution has one free parameter and does not allow for the variance to be adjusted independently of the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] The choice of a distribution from the Poisson family is often dictated by the nature of the empirical data.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] For example, Poisson regression analysis is commonly used to model count data.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] If overdispersion is a feature, an alternative model with additional free parameters may provide a better fit.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] As a more concrete example, it has been observed that the number of boys born to families does not conform faithfully to a binomial distribution as might be expected.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] In this case, the beta-binomial model distribution is a popular and analytically tractable alternative model to the binomial distribution since it provides a better fit to the observed data.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] To capture the heterogeneity of the families, one can think of the probability parameter of the binomial model (say, probability of being a boy) is itself a random variable (i.e. random effects model) drawn for each family from a beta distribution as the mixing distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] The resulting compound distribution (beta-binomial) has an additional free parameter.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Another common model for overdispersion—when some of the observations are not Bernoulli—arises from introducing a normal random variable into a logistic model.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Software is widely available for fitting this type of multilevel model.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] In this case, if the variance of the normal variable is zero, the model reduces to the standard (undispersed) logistic regression.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] This model has an additional free parameter, namely the variance of the normal variable.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] With respect to binomial random variables, the concept of overdispersion makes sense only if n>1 (i.e. overdispersion is nonsensical for Bernoulli random variables).
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] As the normal distribution (Gaussian) has variance as a parameter, any data with finite variance (including any finite data) can be modeled with a normal distribution with the exact variance – the normal distribution is a two-parameter model, with mean and variance.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Thus, in the absence of an underlying model, there is no notion of data being overdispersed relative to the normal model, though the fit may be poor in other respects (such as the higher moments of skew, kurtosis, etc.).
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] However, in the case that the data is modeled by a normal distribution with an expected variation, it can be over- or under-dispersed relative to that prediction.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] For example, in a statistical survey, the margin of error (determined by sample size) predicts the sampling error and hence dispersion of results on repeated surveys.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] If one performs a meta-analysis of repeated surveys of a fixed population (say with a given sample size, so margin of error is the same), one expects the results to fall on normal distribution with standard deviation equal to the margin of error.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] However, in the presence of study heterogeneity where studies have different sampling bias, the distribution is instead a compound distribution and will be overdistributed relative to the predicted distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] For example, given repeated opinion polls all with a margin of error of 3%, if they are conducted by different polling organizations, one expects the results to have standard deviation greater than 3%, due to pollster bias from different methodologies.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Over- and underdispersion are terms which have been adopted in branches of the biological sciences.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] In parasitology, the term 'overdispersion' is generally used as defined here – meaning a distribution with a higher than expected variance.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] In some areas of ecology, however, meanings have been transposed, so that overdispersion is actually taken to mean more even (lower variance) than expected.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] This confusion has caused some ecologists to suggest that the terms 'aggregated', or 'contagious', would be better used in ecology for 'overdispersed'.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Such preferences are creeping into parasitology too.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Generally this suggestion has not been heeded, and confusion persists in the literature.
[src:poisson-regression/overdispersion] Furthermore in demography, overdispersion is often evident in the analysis of death count data, but demographers prefer the term 'unobserved heterogeneity'.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] It can also be used for the number of events in other types of intervals than time, and in dimension greater than 1 (e.g., number of events in a given area or volume).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution is named after French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] It plays an important role for discrete-stable distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Under a Poisson distribution with the expectation of λ events in a given interval, the probability of k events in the same interval is: ${\frac {\lambda ^{k}e^{-\lambda }}{k!}}.$ For instance, consider a call center which receives an average of *λ* = 3 calls per minute at all times of day.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] If the number of calls received in any two given disjoint time intervals is independent, then the number k of calls received during any minute has a Poisson probability distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Receiving *k* = 1 to 4 calls then has a probability of about 0.77, while receiving 0 or at least 5 calls has a probability of about 0.23.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] A classic example used to motivate the Poisson distribution is the number of radioactive decay events during a fixed observation period.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The introduction of the Poisson distribution is credited to French mathematician and physicist Siméon Denis Poisson (1781–1840), who published it together with his probability theory in *Recherches sur la probabilité des jugements en matière criminelle et en matière civile* (1837).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This work theorizes about the number of wrongful convictions in a given country by focusing on certain random variables N that count the number of events that take place during a time interval of given length.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] However, similar results had already been given in 1711 by Abraham de Moivre in *De Mensura Sortis seu; de Probabilitate Eventuum in Ludis a Casu Fortuito Pendentibus* .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This makes it an example of Stigler's law and it has prompted some authors to argue that the Poisson distribution should bear the name of de Moivre.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In 1860, Simon Newcomb fitted the Poisson distribution to the number of stars found in a unit of space.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] A further practical application was made by Ladislaus Bortkiewicz in 1898.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Bortkiewicz showed that the frequency with which soldiers in the Prussian army were accidentally killed by horse kicks could be well modeled by a Poisson distribution..
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution can be applied to systems with a large number of possible events, each of which is rare.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The number of such events that occur during a fixed time interval is, under the right circumstances, a random number with a Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The equation can be adapted if, instead of the average number of events $\lambda ,$ we are given the average rate r at which events occur.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Examples of the occurrence of random points in space are: the locations of asteroid impacts with earth (2-dimensional), the locations of imperfections in a material (3-dimensional), and the locations of trees in a forest (2-dimensional).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] If these conditions are true, then k is a Poisson random variable; the distribution of k is a Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The number of students who arrive at the student union per minute will likely not follow a Poisson distribution, because the rate is not constant (low rate during class time, high rate between class times) and the arrivals of individual students are not independent (students tend to come in groups).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The non-constant arrival rate may be modeled as a mixed Poisson distribution, and the arrival of groups rather than individual students as a compound Poisson process.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The number of magnitude 5 earthquakes per year in a country may not follow a Poisson distribution if one large earthquake increases the probability of aftershocks of similar magnitude.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Examples in which at least one event is guaranteed are not Poisson distributed; but may be modeled using a zero-truncated Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Count distributions in which the number of intervals with zero events is higher than predicted by a Poisson model may be modeled using a zero-inflated model.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The higher non-centered moments *m**k* of the Poisson distribution are Touchard polynomials in λ: $m_{k}=\sum _{i=0}^{k}\lambda ^{i}{\begin{Bmatrix}k\\i\end{Bmatrix}},$ where the braces { } denote Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In other words, $E[X]=\lambda ,\quad E[X(X-1)]=\lambda ^{2},\quad E[X(X-1)(X-2)]=\lambda ^{3},\cdots$ When the expected value is set to *λ* = 1, Dobinski's formula implies that the n‑th moment is equal to the number of partitions of a set of size n.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] It is a maximum-entropy distribution among the set of generalized binomial distributions $B_{n}(\lambda )$ with mean $\lambda$ and $n\to \infty$ , where a generalized binomial distribution is defined as a distribution of the sum of N independent but not identically distributed Bernoulli variables.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The upper bound is proved using a standard Chernoff bound.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Further noting that $X+Y\sim \operatorname {Pois} (\lambda +\mu ),$ and computing a lower bound on the unconditional probability gives the result.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] More details can be found in the appendix of Kamath et al.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution can be derived as a limiting case to the binomial distribution as the number of trials goes to infinity and the expected number of successes remains fixed — see law of rare events below.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Therefore, it can be used as an approximation of the binomial distribution if n is sufficiently large and p is sufficiently small.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution is a good approximation of the binomial distribution if n is at least 20 and p is smaller than or equal to 0.05, and an excellent approximation if *n* ≥ 100 and *np* ≤ 10.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Letting $F_{\mathrm {B} }$ and $F_{\mathrm {P} }$ be the respective cumulative density functions of the binomial and Poisson distributions, one has: $F_{\mathrm {B} }(k;n,p)\ \approx \ F_{\mathrm {P} }(k;\lambda =np).$ One derivation of this uses probability-generating functions.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Consider a Bernoulli trial (coin-flip) whose probability of one success (or expected number of successes) is $\lambda \leq 1$ within a given interval.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Split the interval into n parts, and perform a trial in each subinterval with probability ${\tfrac {\lambda }{n}}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The factor of $e{\sqrt {m}}$ can be replaced by 2 if f is further assumed to be monotonically increasing or decreasing.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This distribution has been extended to the bivariate case.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The free Poisson distribution with jump size $\alpha$ and rate $\lambda$ arises in free probability theory as the limit of repeated free convolution $\left(\left(1-{\frac {\lambda }{N}}\right)\delta _{0}+{\frac {\lambda }{N}}\delta _{\alpha }\right)^{\boxplus N}$ as *N* → ∞.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In other words, let $X_{N}$ be random variables so that $X_{N}$ has value $\alpha$ with probability ${\textstyle {\frac {\lambda }{N}}}$ and value 0 with the remaining probability.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Assume also that the family $X_{1},X_{2},\ldots$ are freely independent.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This definition is analogous to one of the ways in which the classical Poisson distribution is obtained from a (classical) Poisson process.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This law also arises in random matrix theory as the Marchenko–Pastur law.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] We give values of some important transforms of the free Poisson law; the computation can be found in e.g. in the book *Lectures on the Combinatorics of Free Probability* by A.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Given a sample of n measured values $k_{i}\in \{0,1,\dots \},$ for *i* = 1, ..., *n*, we wish to estimate the value of the parameter λ of the Poisson population from which the sample was drawn.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Since each observation has expectation λ, so does the sample mean.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Therefore, the maximum likelihood estimate is an unbiased estimator of λ.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] It is also an efficient estimator since its variance achieves the Cramér–Rao lower bound (CRLB).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Also it can be proven that the sum (and hence the sample mean as it is a one-to-one function of the sum) is a complete and sufficient statistic for λ.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] To prove sufficiency we may use the factorization theorem.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The first term $h(\mathbf {x} )$ depends only on $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The second term $g(T(\mathbf {x} )|\lambda )$ depends on the sample only through ${\textstyle T(\mathbf {x} )=\sum _{i=1}^{n}x_{i}.}$ Thus, $T(\mathbf {x} )$ is sufficient.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] So λ is the average of the *k**i* values.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Obtaining the sign of the second derivative of L at the stationary point will determine what kind of extreme value λ is.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] which is the negative of n times the reciprocal of the average of the *k**i*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This expression is negative when the average is positive.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] If this is satisfied, then the stationary point maximizes the probability function.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For this equality to hold, $g(t)$ must be 0.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This follows from the fact that none of the other terms will be 0 for all t in the sum and for all possible values of $\lambda .$ Hence, $E(g(T))=0$ for all $\lambda$ implies that $P_{\lambda }(g(T)=0)=1,$ and the statistic has been shown to be complete.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The confidence interval for the mean of a Poisson distribution can be expressed using the relationship between the cumulative distribution functions of the Poisson and chi-squared distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The chi-squared distribution is itself closely related to the gamma distribution, and this leads to an alternative expression.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] where $\chi ^{2}(p;n)$ is the quantile function (corresponding to a lower tail area p) of the chi-squared distribution with n degrees of freedom and $F^{-1}(p;n,1)$ is the quantile function of a gamma distribution with shape parameter n and scale parameter 1.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This interval is 'exact' in the sense that its coverage probability is never less than the nominal 1 – *α*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] $k=\sum _{i=1}^{n}k_{i},$ calculate an interval for *μ* = *nλ*, and then derive the interval for λ.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In Bayesian inference, the conjugate prior for the rate parameter λ of the Poisson distribution is the gamma distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Note that the posterior mean is linear and is given by $E[\lambda \mid k_{1},\ldots ,k_{n}]={\frac {\alpha +\sum _{i=1}^{n}k_{i}}{\beta +n}}.$ It can be shown that gamma distribution is the only prior that induces linearity of the conditional mean.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Moreover, a converse result exists which states that if the conditional mean is close to a linear function in the $L_{2}$ distance than the prior distribution of λ must be close to gamma distribution in Levy distance.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The posterior mean E[*λ*] approaches the maximum likelihood estimate ${\widehat {\lambda }}_{\mathrm {MLE} }$ in the limit as $\alpha \to 0,\beta \to 0,$ which follows immediately from the general expression of the mean of the gamma distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The posterior predictive distribution for a single additional observation is a negative binomial distribution, sometimes called a gamma–Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Suppose $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{p}$ is a set of independent random variables from a set of p Poisson distributions, each with a parameter $\lambda _{i},$ $i=1,\dots ,p,$ and we would like to estimate these parameters.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In probabilistic number theory, Gallagher showed in 1976 that, if a certain version of the unproved prime r-tuple conjecture holds, then the counts of prime numbers in short intervals would obey a Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The rate of an event is related to the probability of an event occurring in some small subinterval (of time, space or otherwise).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In the case of the Poisson distribution, one assumes that there exists a small enough subinterval for which the probability of an event occurring twice is "negligible".
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] With this assumption one can derive the Poisson distribution from the binomial one, given only the information of expected number of total events in the whole interval.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Let the total number of events in the whole interval be denoted by $\lambda .$ Divide the whole interval into n subintervals $I_{1},\dots ,I_{n}$ of equal size, such that $n>\lambda$ (since we are interested in only very small portions of the interval this assumption is meaningful).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Hence for each subdivision of the interval we have approximated the occurrence of the event as a Bernoulli process of the form ${\textrm {B}}(n,\lambda /n).$ As we have noted before we want to consider only very small subintervals.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Therefore, we take the limit as n goes to infinity.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In this case the binomial distribution converges to what is known as the Poisson distribution by the Poisson limit theorem.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In such cases n is very large and p is very small (and so the expectation np is of intermediate magnitude).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] This approximation is sometimes known as the *law of rare events*, since each of the n individual Bernoulli events rarely occurs.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The name "law of rare events" may be misleading because the total count of success events in a Poisson process need not be rare if the parameter np is not small.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The variance of the binomial distribution is 1 − *p* times that of the Poisson distribution, so almost equal when p is very small.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The word *law* is sometimes used as a synonym of probability distribution, and *convergence in law* means *convergence in distribution*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Accordingly, the Poisson distribution is sometimes called the "law of small numbers" because it is the probability distribution of the number of occurrences of an event that happens rarely but has very many opportunities to happen.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] *The Law of Small Numbers* is a book by Ladislaus Bortkiewicz about the Poisson distribution, published in 1898.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution arises as the number of points of a Poisson point process located in some finite region.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Poisson regression and negative binomial regression are useful for analyses where the dependent (response) variable is the count (0, 1, 2, ... ) of the number of events or occurrences in an interval.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Luria–Delbrück experiment tested against the hypothesis of Lamarckian evolution, which should result in a Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Katz and Miledi measured the membrane potential with and without the presence of acetylcholine (ACh).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] When ACh is present, ion channels on the membrane would be open randomly at a small fraction of the time.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] As there are a large number of ion channels each open for a small fraction of the time, the total number of ion channels open at any moment is Poisson distributed.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] When ACh is not present, effectively no ion channels are open.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Subtracting the effect of noise, Katz and Miledi found the mean and variance of membrane potential to be $8.5\times 10^{-3}\;\mathrm {V}$ and $(29.2\times 10^{-6}\;\mathrm {V} )^{2}$ respectively, giving $V_{\text{ion}}=10^{-7}\;\mathrm {V}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] During each cellular replication event, the number of mutations is roughly Poisson distributed.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For example, the HIV virus has 10,000 base pairs, and has a mutation rate of about 1 per 30,000 base pairs, meaning the number of mutations per replication event is distributed as $\mathrm {Pois} (1/3)$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In a Poisson process, the number of observed occurrences fluctuates about its mean λ with a standard deviation $\sigma _{k}={\sqrt {\lambda }}.$ These fluctuations are denoted as *Poisson noise* or (particularly in electronics) as *shot noise*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The correlation of the mean and standard deviation in counting independent discrete occurrences is useful scientifically.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] By monitoring how the fluctuations vary with the mean signal, one can estimate the contribution of a single occurrence, *even if that contribution is too small to be detected directly*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For example, the charge e on an electron can be estimated by correlating the magnitude of an electric current with its shot noise.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] An everyday example is the graininess that appears as photographs are enlarged; the graininess is due to Poisson fluctuations in the number of reduced silver grains, not to the individual grains themselves.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] By correlating the graininess with the degree of enlargement, one can estimate the contribution of an individual grain (which is otherwise too small to be seen unaided).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] In causal set theory the discrete elements of spacetime follow a Poisson distribution in the volume.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution also appears in quantum mechanics, especially quantum optics.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Namely, for a quantum harmonic oscillator system in a coherent state, the probability of measuring a particular energy level has a Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The Poisson distribution poses two different tasks for dedicated software libraries: *evaluating* the distribution $P(k;\lambda )$ , and *drawing random numbers* according to that distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Computing $P(k;\lambda )$ for given k and $\lambda$ is a trivial task that can be accomplished by using the standard definition of $P(k;\lambda )$ in terms of exponential, power, and factorial functions.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] However, the conventional definition of the Poisson distribution contains two terms that can easily overflow on computers: *λ**k* and *k*!.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The fraction of *λ**k* to *k*! can also produce a rounding error that is very large compared to *e*−*λ*, and therefore give an erroneous result.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For numerical stability the Poisson probability mass function should therefore be evaluated as $\!f(k;\lambda )=\exp \left[k\ln \lambda -\lambda -\ln \Gamma (k+1)\right],$ which is mathematically equivalent but numerically stable.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The natural logarithm of the Gamma function can be obtained using the `lgamma` function in the C standard library (C99 version) or R, the `gammaln` function in MATLAB or SciPy, or the `log_gamma` function in Fortran 2008 and later.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The complexity is linear in the returned value k, which is λ on average.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] There are many other algorithms to improve this.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Some are given in Ahrens & Dieter, see § References below.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For large values of λ, the value of *L* = *e*−*λ* may be so small that it is hard to represent.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] The choice of STEP depends on the threshold of overflow.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] For double precision floating point format the threshold is near *e*700, so 500 should be a safe *STEP*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Other solutions for large values of λ include rejection sampling and using Gaussian approximation.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Inverse transform sampling is simple and efficient for small values of λ, and requires only one uniform random number u per sample.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-distribution] Cumulative probabilities are examined in turn until one exceeds u.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] In statistics, **Poisson regression** is a generalized linear model form of regression analysis used to model count data and contingency tables.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Poisson regression assumes the response variable *Y* has a Poisson distribution, and assumes the logarithm of its expected value can be modeled by a linear combination of unknown parameters.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] A Poisson regression model is sometimes known as a log-linear model, especially when used to model contingency tables.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Poisson regression models are generalized linear models with the logarithm as the (canonical) link function, and the Poisson distribution function as the assumed probability distribution of the response.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] where $\alpha \in \mathbb {R}$ and $\mathbf {\beta } \in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] where $\mathbf {x}$ is now an (*n* + 1)-dimensional vector consisting of *n* independent variables concatenated to the number one.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Here $\theta$ is simply $\beta$ concatenated to $\alpha$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] If $Y_{i}$ are independent observations with corresponding values $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ of the predictor variables, then $\theta$ can be estimated by maximum likelihood.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] The maximum-likelihood estimates lack a closed-form expression and must be found by numerical methods.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] The probability surface for maximum-likelihood Poisson regression is always concave, making Newton–Raphson or other gradient-based methods appropriate estimation techniques.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] So the coefficient of the model is to be interpreted as the increase in the logarithm of the count of the outcome variable when the independent variable increases by 1.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] That is, when the independent variable increases by 1, the outcome variable is multiplied by the exponentiated coefficient.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] The exponentiated coefficient is also called the *incidence ratio*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Often, the object of interest is the average partial effect or average marginal effect ${\frac {\partial E(Y|x)}{\partial x}}$ , which is interpreted as the change in the outcome Y for a one unit change in the independent variable x .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] This can be estimated using the coefficient estimates from the Poisson model ${\hat {\theta }}=({\hat {\alpha }},{\hat {\beta }})$ with the observed values of $\mathbb {x}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Now suppose we are given a data set consisting of *m* vectors $x_{i}\in \mathbb {R} ^{n+1},\,i=1,\ldots ,m$ , along with a set of *m* values $y_{1},\ldots ,y_{m}\in \mathbb {N}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] By the method of maximum likelihood, we wish to find the set of parameters *θ* that makes this probability as large as possible.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Note that the expression on the right hand side has not actually changed.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Notice that the parameters *θ* only appear in the first two terms of each term in the summation.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] To find a maximum, we need to solve an equation ${\frac {\partial \ell (\theta \mid X,Y)}{\partial \theta }}=0$ which has no closed-form solution.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] However, the negative log-likelihood, $-\ell (\theta \mid X,Y)$ , is a convex function, and so standard convex optimization techniques such as gradient descent can be applied to find the optimal value of *θ*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Poisson regression may be appropriate when the dependent variable is a count, for instance of events such as the arrival of a telephone call at a call centre.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] The events must be independent in the sense that the arrival of one call will not make another more or less likely, but the probability per unit time of events is understood to be related to covariates such as time of day.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Poisson regression may also be appropriate for rate data, where the rate is a count of events divided by some measure of that unit's *exposure* (a particular unit of observation).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] For example, biologists may count the number of tree species in a forest: events would be tree observations, exposure would be unit area, and rate would be the number of species per unit area.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Demographers may model death rates in geographic areas as the count of deaths divided by person−years.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] More generally, event rates can be calculated as events per unit time, which allows the observation window to vary for each unit.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] In these examples, exposure is respectively unit area, person−years and unit time.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] In Poisson regression this is handled as an **offset**.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] If the rate is count/exposure, multiplying both sides of the equation by exposure moves it to the right side of the equation.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] When both sides of the equation are then logged, the final model contains log(exposure) as a term that is added to the regression coefficients.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] This logged variable, log(exposure), is called the offset variable and enters on the right-hand side of the equation with a parameter estimate (for log(exposure)) constrained to 1.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] A characteristic of the Poisson distribution is that its mean is equal to its variance.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] In certain circumstances, it will be found that the observed variance is greater than the mean; this is known as overdispersion and indicates that the model is not appropriate.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] A common reason is the omission of relevant explanatory variables, or dependent observations.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Under some circumstances, the problem of overdispersion can be solved by using quasi-likelihood estimation or a negative binomial distribution instead.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] For both models, parameters are estimated using iteratively reweighted least squares.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] For quasi-Poisson, the weights are *μ*/*θ*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] For negative binomial, the weights are *μ*/(1 + *κμ*).
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] With large *μ* and substantial extra-Poisson variation, the negative binomial weights are capped at 1/*κ*.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Ver Hoef and Boveng discussed an example where they selected between the two by plotting mean squared residuals vs. the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Another common problem with Poisson regression is excess zeros: if there are two processes at work, one determining whether there are zero events or any events, and a Poisson process determining how many events there are, there will be more zeros than a Poisson regression would predict.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] An example would be the distribution of cigarettes smoked in an hour by members of a group where some individuals are non-smokers.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Other generalized linear models such as the negative binomial model or zero-inflated model may function better in these cases.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] On the contrary, underdispersion may pose an issue for parameter estimation.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] Poisson regression creates proportional hazards models, one class of survival analysis: see proportional hazards models for descriptions of Cox models.
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] where *m* is the number of examples in the data set, and $p(y_{i};e^{\theta 'x_{i}})$ is the probability mass function of the Poisson distribution with the mean set to $e^{\theta 'x_{i}}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/poisson-regression] This technique, similar to ridge regression, can reduce overfitting.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] In statistics, a **zero-inflated model** is a statistical model based on a zero-inflated probability distribution, i.e. a distribution that allows for frequent zero-valued observations.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Zero-inflated models are commonly used in the analysis of count data, such as the number of visits a patient makes to the emergency room in one year, or the number of fish caught in one day in one lake.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Count data can take values of 0, 1, 2, … (non-negative integer values).
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Other examples of count data are the number of hits recorded by a Geiger counter in one minute, patient days in the hospital, goals scored in a soccer game, and the number of episodes of hypoglycemia per year for a patient with diabetes.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] For statistical analysis, the distribution of the counts is often represented using a Poisson distribution or a negative binomial distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Hilbe notes that "Poisson regression is traditionally conceived of as the basic count model upon which a variety of other count models are based." In a Poisson model, "… the random variable y is the count response and parameter $\lambda$ (lambda) is the mean.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] In some data, the number of zeros is greater than would be expected using a Poisson distribution or a negative binomial distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Data with such an excess of zero counts are described as Zero-inflated.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Example histograms of zero-inflated Poisson distributions with mean $\mu$ of 5 or 10 and proportion of zero inflation $\pi$ of 0.2 or 0.5 are shown below, based on the R program ZeroInflPoiDistPlots.R from Bilder and Laughlin.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] As the examples above show, zero-inflated data can arise as a mixture of two distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] The second distribution, which may be a Poisson distribution, a negative binomial distribution or other count distribution, generates counts, some of which may be zeros.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] In the statistical literature, different authors may use different names to distinguish zeros from the two distributions.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Some authors describe zeros generated by the first (binary) distribution as "structural" and zeros generated by the second (count) distribution as "random".
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Other authors use the terminology "immune" and "susceptible" for the binary and count zeros, respectively.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] One well-known zero-inflated model is Diane Lambert's zero-inflated Poisson model, which concerns a random event containing excess zero-count data in unit time.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] For example, the number of insurance claims within a population for a certain type of risk would be zero-inflated by those people who have not taken out insurance against the risk and thus are unable to claim.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] The zero-inflated Poisson (ZIP) model mixes two zero generating processes.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] The second process is governed by a Poisson distribution that generates counts, some of which may be zero.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] where the outcome variable $y_{i}$ has any non-negative integer value, $\lambda$ is the expected Poisson count for the i th individual; $\pi$ is the probability of extra zeros.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] The mean is $(1-\pi )\lambda$ and the variance is $\lambda (1-\pi )(1+\pi \lambda )$ .
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] where m is the sample mean and $s^{2}$ is the sample variance.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] where ${\frac {n_{0}}{n}}$ is the observed proportion of zeros.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Alternatively, the equation can be solved by iteration.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] In 1994, Greene considered the zero-inflated negative binomial (ZINB) model.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Hall adapted Lambert's methodology to an upper-bounded count situation, thereby obtaining a zero-inflated binomial (ZIB) model.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] then the discrete data Y obey discrete pseudo compound Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] In fact, let $G(z)=\sum \limits _{n=0}^{\infty }P(Y=n)z^{n}$ be the probability generating function of $y_{i}$ .
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] Then from the Wiener–Lévy theorem, $G(z)$ has the probability generating function of the discrete pseudo compound Poisson distribution.
[src:poisson-regression/zero-inflated-model] When all the $\alpha _{k}$ are non-negative, it is the discrete compound Poisson distribution (non-Poisson case) with overdispersion property.
